WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.880
So if you're new to Connect, Connect is an enterprise publishing platform for

00:00:12.880 --> 00:00:16.000
static and dynamic content that you're creating with R. So that can include

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:19.920
documents, presentations, dashboards, and Shiny applications, and basically

00:00:19.920 --> 00:00:23.719
anything that you're producing in R. It is an on-premises application, so you run

00:00:23.719 --> 00:00:28.200
this on your own server behind a firewall if you want, and you're going to host it

00:00:28.400 --> 00:00:32.080
on your own equipment there. And the goal is really around sharing data science

00:00:32.080 --> 00:00:37.320
artifacts that you produced inside your organization. So if this is new to you, I

00:00:37.320 --> 00:00:40.919
would recommend actually that you check out the introductory webinar that Bill

00:00:40.919 --> 00:00:44.380
referenced a moment ago. So we recorded this two weeks ago, the recording is

00:00:44.380 --> 00:00:49.160
available online, as are the slides. And I'd recommend that you start there

00:00:49.160 --> 00:00:51.360
because we're going to be building on some of the foundation that we laid a

00:00:51.360 --> 00:00:55.919
couple weeks ago. So if you are new to Connect, you might want to start there

00:00:55.919 --> 00:01:00.639
before you jump into some of these more advanced topics. But without any further

00:01:00.639 --> 00:01:04.160
ado, let's go ahead and dive into some of the content that we want to cover today.

00:01:04.160 --> 00:01:09.760
So my goal for today is really just to give you pointers to the different

00:01:09.760 --> 00:01:14.080
tidbits that I think are important for you to know if you're going to be

00:01:14.080 --> 00:01:17.680
managing RStudio Connect in a production environment. And so I won't go

00:01:17.680 --> 00:01:21.480
into too much depth about a whole lot of these, but really I just kind of

00:01:21.480 --> 00:01:24.360
want to give you links and pointers to the different things that you might be

00:01:24.400 --> 00:01:28.279
interested in if you are responsible for managing a production environment with

00:01:28.279 --> 00:01:31.559
RStudio Connect. So pardon me if I'm kind of flying through some of these topics,

00:01:31.559 --> 00:01:34.680
but feel free to ask questions and we can come back and do a little more

00:01:34.680 --> 00:01:38.760
detail on some of these things later. Or just check out the links once

00:01:38.760 --> 00:01:43.040
we post them online and hopefully you can kind of find the

00:01:43.040 --> 00:01:47.080
information that you need there with the links that I provide. So today I want to

00:01:47.080 --> 00:01:51.360
cover first of all user management, then secondly the management of resources on

00:01:51.360 --> 00:01:54.480
the server, and then lastly we'll talk a little bit about kind of the system

00:01:54.480 --> 00:01:59.040
management and system security implications for the server. So let's

00:01:59.040 --> 00:02:03.559
dive into user management to get started. So we covered this a bit last time so I

00:02:03.559 --> 00:02:08.479
won't belabor this, but we have three different user roles on the system. The

00:02:08.479 --> 00:02:12.160
first is an admin user who has all privileges on the server and they can

00:02:12.160 --> 00:02:16.639
access and kind of manage anything that they need to, but irregular actions are

00:02:16.639 --> 00:02:20.399
audited and I'll dive into what that means here in a moment. Below that there

00:02:20.399 --> 00:02:23.399
would be a publisher who's someone that can upload or publish content onto the

00:02:23.399 --> 00:02:26.960
server, and then lastly there's a viewer who's just a consumer of content and

00:02:26.960 --> 00:02:32.479
can't author content that gets executed on the server. So let's talk a little bit

00:02:32.479 --> 00:02:36.600
about what the experience of a Connect administrator looks like. So first of

00:02:36.600 --> 00:02:39.919
all they have access to special admin only actions, and so for instance this

00:02:39.919 --> 00:02:45.000
includes the admin tab, so if you're an admin on the user you're able to access

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:48.880
certain pages within the dashboard that other users aren't able to manage that

00:02:48.880 --> 00:02:52.080
shows you things like metrics, you're able to manage users and things like

00:02:52.080 --> 00:02:56.240
that, and then lastly you're able to customize some application settings that

00:02:56.240 --> 00:02:59.720
other users aren't able to. So you can define vanity URLs for an application,

00:02:59.720 --> 00:03:02.800
you can customize the run as argument for an application, and I'll show you

00:03:02.800 --> 00:03:06.559
what all this means here in just a moment. But the trick is that you don't

00:03:06.559 --> 00:03:10.559
get everything for free as an admin, and so some of these things you're going to

00:03:10.559 --> 00:03:14.000
be able to just hop on and start changing. Other things you're going to

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:18.279
actually have to go out of your way to explicitly grant yourself permission to

00:03:18.279 --> 00:03:22.479
things that you otherwise wouldn't have had permission to do. So let's, I think

00:03:22.479 --> 00:03:25.720
that's probably best covered by just an example, so let's look at an example of

00:03:25.720 --> 00:03:31.240
this. So first of all this is me logged in as an admin user on Connect.

00:03:31.240 --> 00:03:36.000
And so you can see here that first of all I have this admin tab, and so that

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:39.440
takes me first and foremost to this metrics page where I'm able to view

00:03:39.440 --> 00:03:43.199
information about the CPU and RAM usage across the server. I also have an audit

00:03:43.199 --> 00:03:47.119
logs page here where I can view kind of different changes that have been taking

00:03:47.119 --> 00:03:52.279
place on the server recently. And then lastly when I dive into particular

00:03:52.279 --> 00:03:56.520
content, even though this is not authored by me, this is authored by someone else

00:03:56.520 --> 00:03:59.919
and I don't have particular permissions on it, I am still able to go in and

00:03:59.919 --> 00:04:03.639
define custom settings for this content. So for instance here I can define a

00:04:03.639 --> 00:04:11.440
vanity URL. Let's take a look at kind of a more rich document here. So in this

00:04:11.440 --> 00:04:14.119
case we have a schedule. I as an administrator, even though I don't have

00:04:14.119 --> 00:04:17.239
special privileges on this document, I can go in and customize the schedule for

00:04:17.239 --> 00:04:22.079
this content. I can define a vanity URL, change the run as user, etc. So I

00:04:22.079 --> 00:04:25.760
as an admin have free privileges to be able to do some of these things. However

00:04:25.760 --> 00:04:32.079
if you look at something like a document here that's private, so here I'm logged

00:04:32.079 --> 00:04:35.200
in as a different user, this is the publisher user, and you can see that I

00:04:35.200 --> 00:04:38.920
for this content here I've defined it to only be visible to myself. So this means

00:04:38.920 --> 00:04:42.040
that the admin user should not freely have access to this content. This is

00:04:42.040 --> 00:04:45.720
sensitive content that the admin shouldn't be able to see. And indeed if I

00:04:45.720 --> 00:04:49.480
go as the admin and I go to look at that content, this is the view that I get. So

00:04:49.480 --> 00:04:52.239
you can see that I'm still able to manage the settings for that content

00:04:52.239 --> 00:04:59.119
here, but I do not have free access to be able to view that content. And so this is

00:04:59.119 --> 00:05:02.320
kind of what we're talking about when we say the admin has the privileges to do

00:05:02.320 --> 00:05:04.959
whatever they need to do on the server, but they don't get everything for free.

00:05:04.959 --> 00:05:09.559
So I am not able to view this content, although I can go in and I can add

00:05:09.559 --> 00:05:13.760
myself as a publisher or as a viewer because I'm able to manage the settings

00:05:13.760 --> 00:05:17.720
on this content, and at that point I would be able to view the content. And so

00:05:17.720 --> 00:05:24.200
the trick here is that all of this though is managed when you make these

00:05:24.200 --> 00:05:28.480
explicit actions to add or remove yourself to a particular bit of content,

00:05:28.480 --> 00:05:31.799
all of those actions are going to be captured in the audit log that I

00:05:31.799 --> 00:05:34.959
referenced earlier. So when I go look at the audit log you can see here that the

00:05:34.959 --> 00:05:38.600
admin user assigned themselves as an owner as a collaborator on this app and

00:05:38.640 --> 00:05:42.799
then they remove themselves as an owner as a collaborator on this app. So now while I am

00:05:42.799 --> 00:05:46.920
able to do everything and navigate whatever I need to cover to be able to

00:05:46.920 --> 00:05:52.040
manage the server, anytime I take those explicit options of kind of going out of

00:05:52.040 --> 00:05:55.399
my way to take special privileges on an application, that's going to be captured

00:05:55.399 --> 00:05:58.119
in the audit log and that's kind of the balance that we try to strike here with

00:05:58.119 --> 00:06:05.040
an admin. Lastly, if you've missed this in our latest release, the 1.441 release, we

00:06:05.040 --> 00:06:09.359
also do have the ability to download the source code for content. And again

00:06:09.359 --> 00:06:12.519
that's only available to users that are explicitly granted

00:06:12.519 --> 00:06:16.160
collaborator privileges. So I as an admin do not get free access to source

00:06:16.160 --> 00:06:20.079
codes published on the server, however if I add myself as a collaborator then I am

00:06:20.079 --> 00:06:24.079
able to download the source code for an application. So this is kind of the

00:06:24.079 --> 00:06:26.880
balance that we tried to strike with an admin but I think it's important if

00:06:26.880 --> 00:06:30.160
you're going to be managing a Connect server in production that you kind of

00:06:30.160 --> 00:06:33.399
understand what the privileges of an admin actually encapsulate and what you

00:06:33.399 --> 00:06:38.399
get for free and what you don't. So next we'll just kind of move on and a lot of

00:06:38.399 --> 00:06:41.359
these things I'm just going to cover in rapid fire, but the next one that I

00:06:41.359 --> 00:06:45.040
wanted to cover is the default user role. So this is the setting that's managed in

00:06:45.040 --> 00:06:48.760
the authorization section under the default user role setting and this is

00:06:48.760 --> 00:06:51.399
basically the role that fresh users should take when they sign on to the

00:06:51.399 --> 00:06:54.559
server. The default right now is publisher, which means that when a user

00:06:54.559 --> 00:06:57.720
signs up on your server or when they you know log in using whatever

00:06:57.720 --> 00:07:01.399
authentication protocol you're using, that user is going to become a publisher

00:07:01.399 --> 00:07:04.279
on the server, they're going to have access to publish new source code. If you

00:07:04.279 --> 00:07:07.760
want to change that, if you want to limit that so that default so that new users

00:07:07.760 --> 00:07:11.359
coming into the server are just viewers, you can change this configuration

00:07:11.359 --> 00:07:14.519
setting here and make that a viewer. And this is actually subject to change, we've

00:07:14.519 --> 00:07:18.279
considered actually making the default viewer and so in which case if you

00:07:18.279 --> 00:07:21.959
wanted the default to be a publisher you could of course override that here.

00:07:21.959 --> 00:07:25.239
Another tool that you should be aware of if you're managing Connect is the user

00:07:25.239 --> 00:07:28.559
manager command line interface and this is a root only command line interface

00:07:28.559 --> 00:07:32.559
that allows you to interact with Connect in kind of a batch way. And so

00:07:32.559 --> 00:07:34.760
right now there's kind of a limited subset of what you can do with this

00:07:34.760 --> 00:07:37.720
command but we envision this growing over time to capture more of the

00:07:37.720 --> 00:07:41.000
interactions that you might want to take within Connect. So right now one

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:43.600
restriction is that the server actually does need to be stopped in order for you

00:07:43.600 --> 00:07:47.239
for you to use the command line interface here and that that's a

00:07:47.239 --> 00:07:50.440
restriction that may be lifted here in the coming months. But right now you can

00:07:50.440 --> 00:07:54.359
access the tool at this location, optr-studio-connect-bin-user-manager and

00:07:54.359 --> 00:07:58.079
then you can run commands such as list to list all the users in the server, you

00:07:58.079 --> 00:08:02.200
can run alter to change a user for instance promoting a viewer to a

00:08:02.200 --> 00:08:06.320
publisher or promoting a publisher to an admin user, and you can also actually

00:08:06.320 --> 00:08:11.040
dump the audit logs even in the CSV format here. So if you wanted to navigate

00:08:11.040 --> 00:08:14.839
and browse the audit logs on your own time or using your own tooling you could

00:08:14.839 --> 00:08:18.239
do that here using this user manager tool. So something you should be aware of

00:08:18.239 --> 00:08:21.720
and you can view all the documents in the admin guide for what different

00:08:21.720 --> 00:08:27.480
endpoints are available in this command. Next there's an idea of user locking in

00:08:27.480 --> 00:08:30.920
the server that you should be familiar with. So as of the time of this

00:08:30.920 --> 00:08:36.679
recording in early 2017 we don't have a notion of user deletion and the reason

00:08:36.679 --> 00:08:40.159
for that is that there are a lot of open questions around what should you do with

00:08:40.159 --> 00:08:44.479
a user who's deleted, what should you do with their content, should you migrate it

00:08:44.479 --> 00:08:47.520
to another user, should you keep it alive on the server, or should you get rid of

00:08:47.520 --> 00:08:51.520
it. So until we settle some of those questions right now we've kind of

00:08:51.520 --> 00:08:54.679
settled on this compromise of user locking. So if you for instance have an

00:08:54.679 --> 00:08:58.000
employee leave the company and you don't want them to have access to the

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:01.640
server anymore you can lock their account which forbids any further login

00:09:01.640 --> 00:09:04.640
or interaction on the system, they can't publish updates or new content to the

00:09:04.640 --> 00:09:08.200
server, and they also don't count against your license so they're not going to

00:09:08.200 --> 00:09:10.919
count as a named user, they're not going to take up the seat for your license

00:09:10.919 --> 00:09:15.559
when they're locked. And also you should be aware that you can rename users and

00:09:15.559 --> 00:09:18.719
so if your goal is just to get rid of a user who's taking up a username that you

00:09:18.719 --> 00:09:22.400
want you can certainly just change the username for that user and lock it and

00:09:22.400 --> 00:09:27.440
then create a new user account with the username that you desire. So that's a bit

00:09:27.440 --> 00:09:30.280
about user management and we can transition into resource management now

00:09:30.280 --> 00:09:34.159
which is a bit more of a complex topic. So one of the most common questions that

00:09:34.159 --> 00:09:37.159
we get around Connect is the idea of resource budgeting or how large should

00:09:37.159 --> 00:09:41.799
my server be, and the problem or the difficulty in answering this question is

00:09:41.799 --> 00:09:46.640
that the requirements here almost depend entirely on what your users are

00:09:46.640 --> 00:09:51.880
deploying. So if you just have a couple of simple documents that you know are a

00:09:51.880 --> 00:09:55.000
couple of simple dashboards that are updated once a day that people are going

00:09:55.000 --> 00:09:57.760
to access on your Connect server, you could probably get away with some

00:09:57.760 --> 00:10:01.159
running this on you know something like very very small even you know a Raspberry

00:10:01.159 --> 00:10:05.159
Pi could probably handle that kind of workload. However if you're doing you

00:10:05.159 --> 00:10:09.039
know very intensive shiny applications that are doing you know genomic analysis

00:10:09.039 --> 00:10:13.320
on multiple gigabytes of data, then your server requirements are going to be much

00:10:13.320 --> 00:10:16.440
much larger. And so ideally if you if you have the luxury of being in a

00:10:16.440 --> 00:10:19.520
virtualized environment where you can kind of scale up or down a server that

00:10:19.719 --> 00:10:23.719
would probably be your best bet. But otherwise if not you can kind of run a

00:10:23.719 --> 00:10:28.479
proof of concept and see what the hardware requirements are given the

00:10:28.479 --> 00:10:31.960
applications and the types of work that your that your users are publishing to

00:10:31.960 --> 00:10:35.440
the server, and that's really the best way to kind of get a feel for what your

00:10:35.440 --> 00:10:41.359
requirements should be in terms of hardware for the server. So in terms of

00:10:41.359 --> 00:10:44.479
the philosophy of Connect, on-demand requests are largely what we're

00:10:44.479 --> 00:10:47.640
servicing when when requests are coming in, and those are just going to be

00:10:47.640 --> 00:10:50.760
service-best efforts. So you know as a request comes in for a shiny application

00:10:50.760 --> 00:10:53.880
we're going to do our best to spin up that shiny application and hope that

00:10:53.880 --> 00:10:58.320
there's enough memory available on the server. So but there are some knobs and

00:10:58.320 --> 00:11:02.000
some tuning that you can do to cap the resource requirements available to

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:08.000
particular applications or different different use cases. So first of all

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:13.119
that around shiny there's there's a notion of shiny scaling. So you can scale

00:11:13.119 --> 00:11:16.280
shiny applications and connect to multiple processes. So if you're not

00:11:16.280 --> 00:11:20.119
aware R is single-threaded and connect can actually load balance a particular

00:11:20.119 --> 00:11:24.000
application across multiple independent R processes running that same

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:27.960
application. And so this is what's managed here in the performance tab on a

00:11:27.960 --> 00:11:32.359
shiny app. So as an admin you can go in and you can override particular

00:11:32.359 --> 00:11:35.559
performance settings for an application and set for instance the number of max

00:11:35.559 --> 00:11:39.719
processes, how many processes you know under the heaviest load that you might

00:11:39.719 --> 00:11:43.280
be willing to run for this application. And then down at the bottom here you can

00:11:43.280 --> 00:11:46.039
see kind of some of the scaling parameters around how many connections

00:11:46.039 --> 00:11:49.039
should be supported per process. And then the load factor is basically how

00:11:49.039 --> 00:11:51.960
quickly do you want to ramp up from the minimum number of processes to the

00:11:51.960 --> 00:11:55.359
maximum number of processes as load increases. The minimum number of

00:11:55.359 --> 00:12:00.200
processes as the name implies is the is going to guarantee that in processes are

00:12:00.200 --> 00:12:04.919
running for this application at all times. The right answer for this for

00:12:04.919 --> 00:12:08.359
almost all applications is zero. However if you have an application that takes a

00:12:08.359 --> 00:12:11.919
really long time to start up and you don't want a user hitting it having to

00:12:11.919 --> 00:12:16.400
wait multiple seconds or even minutes for the shiny

